The sizes and morphologies of the as-prepared samples were characterized by FESEM and TEM measurements. A representative FESEM image (Fig. 3
                     a) shows that the Ni(OH)2 possesses a regular platelet-like morphology, and the width of a Ni(OH)2 sheet is about 361.1 nm (Fig. S3). From the TEM image of Ni(OH)2 (Fig. 3b), it can be seen that most of the nanosheets on the copper grid are lying with their bigger basal plane with some of them standing on their side edges. The thickness of the Ni(OH)2 nanosheets is about 35.1 nm (Fig. S4). As shown in Fig. 3c and d, the Ni(OH)2/NCDs-2 composites also has platelet-like morphology. However, compared with bare Ni(OH)2 nanosheets in the absence of NCDs, the Ni(OH)2 nanosheets in the composites are smaller with a width of 87.0 nm and a thickness of about 9.8 nm. This result indicates that the NCDs has a great effect on the size of Ni(OH)2 nanosheets in Ni(OH)2/NCDs composites. It has been proposed that when NCDs are incorporated in the reaction, they will coat on the newly formed Ni(OH)2 nuclei and hamper the growth of the Ni(OH)2 nanosheets, and finally result in a smaller size of Ni(OH)2 nanosheets in Ni(OH)2/NCDs nanosheets [19]. The higher the content of NCDs, the heavier the prevention on the growth of Ni(OH)2 nanosheets is. The width and thickness of Ni(OH)2 nanosheets can be further decreased to 73.1 and 7.6 nm when the feeding amount of NCDs was increased to 30 mg (Ni(OH)2/NCDs-3), as shown in Figs. S3–S5. From Fig. 3e, it can be seen that the NCDs (marked with red circles) are effectively anchored on Ni(OH)2 nanosheet surface to form the hybrid structure. Furthermore, the HRTEM image (Fig. 3f) demonstrates clear lattice fringes with a lattice spacing of about 0.233 nm, which can be assigned to the (1 0 1) crystal plane of hexagonal structure Ni(OH)2. The NCDsare observed to be amorphous carbon particles without any lattices. This phenomenon is consistent with previous study [21,30]. To evaluate the elemental distribution of the as-prepared Ni(OH)2/NCDs nanosheets, elemental-mapping analysis was performed. From the elemental mapping images of Ni(OH)2/NCDs-2 nanosheets (Fig. 4
                     ), it can be clearly seen that the elements of Ni, O and N show highly homogeneous distribution in the nanosheets, which suggests the uniform distribution of NCDs on the surface of Ni(OH)2 nanosheets. The nitrogen adsorption/desorption isotherms and porosity of the sample were investigated by BET technique. As shown in Fig. S6, the specific surface area of Ni(OH)2/NCDs-2 is about 136.0 m2 g−1 according to the BET model. In addition, the sample exhibits a porous structure with a pore size distribution from 2 to 30 nm, and the main pore diameter locates at about 23 nm. Such porous structures can facilitate the rapid ion transport and charge storage, and provide more electroactive sites for electrochemical reactions owing to a wider choice of accessible channels for electrolyte penetration [31].
